Malaysia Stocks: Berjaya Food, Sarawak Cable, Telekom, Uzma

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-07-27T09:19:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-27/malaysia-stocks-prestariang-scanwolf-telekom-axiata-uzma.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. local-time close in
 Kuala Lumpur .  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index fell 3.6 points, or 0.2
percent, to 1,558.17.      Berjaya Food Bhd. (BFD MK), a restaurant operator, climbed
2.3 percent to 88 sen, the largest jump since July 1. Berjaya
Food agreed to form a joint venture with PT Mitra Samaya to
develop and operate a Kenny Rogers Roasters franchise on the
Indonesian islands of Java and Bali, according to a company
statement.  Prestariang Bhd. (PRES MK), a communications software
company, slid 18 percent to 74 sen on its debut. The company
sold shares at 90 sen each in its initial public offering.       Scanwolf Corp. (SCW MK), a plastics maker, added 3.4
percent to 46 sen, the most since May 16. Scanwolf said three of
its directors agreed to sell their combined stake of 32 percent
to MKL Resources (L) Ltd. for 13.1 million ringgit ($4.5
million), according a stock-exchange filing.  Sarawak Cable Bhd. (SRCB)  , a power cables and wires
manufacturer, gained 2.6 percent to 2 ringgit, a record close.
Sarawak Cable agreed to form a joint venture with the Malaysian
unit of ABB Ltd. to submit a bid for the construction of a
substation in Sarawak state, according to a stock-exchange
filing.        Telekom Malaysia Bhd. (T)  , the national fixed-line and
Internet services provider, climbed 2 percent to 4.07 ringgit,
the largest gain since May 25. Telekom raised 468.3 million
ringgit by selling 92.36 million shares in  Axiata Group Bhd. (AXIATA) 
, according to a company statement. The shares were
offered to foreign institutional investors at 5.07 ringgit each,
it said. Axiata added 0.2 percent to 5.14 ringgit.        Uzma Bhd. (UZMA)  , an oil and gas engineering services
provider, advanced 3.5 percent to 2.05 ringgit, the highest
level since May 20. Uzma got a 170 million-ringgit contract to
provide integrated equipment and services for an idle-well
reactivation project from Petronas Carigali Sdn., it said in a
statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
